  2.
Tool and Resource Website Links
Provide links to all official websites for tools and resources referenced i=
n the Guide.
  3.
AI and Human Oversight Table
Add a table showing the role of AI, required human oversight, guidance, and=
 outputs for each step in the review process.
Richard is the key contact for this task.
  4.
Visualize the Guide
Break up the flat document structure by adding visual aids and layout impro=
vements.
Joe will take the lead on this.
  5.
High-Level Process Model
Create a visual model that outlines the steps involved in producing a scopi=
ng review.
Include this model at the start of each section, with feedback loops clearl=
y shown.
  6.
Quick Reference Tables
For each step in Part 2 of the Guide, add a one-page reference table includ=
ing:
     *
Objective
     *
Recommended AI tool
     *
Key actions
     *
Expected outputs
  7.
Integrate Grey Literature into the Process
Update Part 2 to explicitly include steps and considerations for grey liter=
ature.
Richard and Sonny are key contributors here.
  8.
Create Instructional Videos
Produce short videos for each major step in the Guide to support learning a=
nd usability.
  9.
Checklist for Human Oversight
Add a checklist that ensures consistent human oversight throughout the scop=
ing review process.

________________________________
III. SEPARATE DOCUMENTS TO PRODUCE

  1.
Human Oversight Workbook
Create a detailed workbook expanding on the human oversight process describ=
ed in the Guide.
  2.
Fill Current Gaps in the Guide
Develop supporting content on:
     *
Risk analysis and project perspective
     *
Project planning tools and traceability
     *
Tool selection and budgeting framework
     *
Use cases extending AI beyond literature reviews
     *
Visualization and decision support systems
     *
Reframing the review as part of the innovation lifecycle
  3.
Inventory of Scoping Reviews
Develop and maintain a catalog of completed scoping reviews that demonstrat=
e effective AI tool use.
  4.
Citation Guide for AI-Assisted Work
Create a guide that explains how to properly cite AI-assisted content in ac=
ademic work, addressing ethical and transparency concerns.
  5.
Simplified and Condensed Versions of the Guide
     *
A beginner-friendly version
     *
A condensed version for experienced researchers
  6.
Multilingual Versions
Translate the Guide into additional languages to support wider access and i=
nclusion.
  7.
Strategy for Rapid AI Development
Develop a flexible framework that allows the Guide to evolve with fast-chan=
ging AI tools.
  8.
Support for Researchers with Limited Access
Provide strategies for those without access to premium AI tools or academic=
 databases.
  9.
Guidelines for Translating Research into Action
Develop a section or supplement that helps researchers apply findings in re=
al-world contexts.


